The `SIGTERM` signal is handled in the manager process only, but not handled in each worker processes. You will need to handle signal `SIGTERM` in worker processes.

Here are two examples to handle signal `SIGTERM` in worker processes.

## If the worker process runs in non-blocking mode:

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

use Swoole\Coroutine;
use Swoole\Process;
use Swoole\Process\Pool;

echo "Current process ID is: ", posix_getpid(), "\n";

$pool = new Pool(2);
$pool->set(['enable_coroutine' => true]);

$pool->on("WorkerStart", function (Pool $pool, int $workerId) {
    Process::signal(SIGTERM, function() use ($pool, $workerId) {
        echo "Will shutdown process #{$workerId}\n";
        // More clean up code before exiting the process.
    });

    $sleep = rand(3, 6);
    echo "Worker #$workerId: sleep for {$sleep} seconds\n";
    Coroutine::sleep($sleep);
});

$pool->on("WorkerStop", function ($pool, $workerId) {
    echo "Worker#$workerId is stopped\n";
    sleep(1);
});

$pool->start();
```

## If the worker process runs in blocking mode:

